Sixth Avenue, north from its convergence with Church Street at White Street, showing this new extension and its subway under construction. The photographer is viewing towards Canal Street. The "El" line shown is on West Broadway. To the right is the towering New York Telephone Company building. This will be included in a new structure that will occupy the entire irregular block between Walker and Lispenard Streets. To the left is the 11-story American Thread Company building. This is on Beach Street, extending from West Broadway to St. Johns Lane. The latter is a small alley way lying between West Broadway and Varick Street. View 3 is photographed from atop a low building on Walker Street(shown in center of View 2).

October 10, 1928
Views 1,2,3

P. L. Sperr

original_title: Manhattan: 6th Avenue - Church Street at White Street.
text:
Sixth Avenue (left) and Church Street (right), north from their convergence at White Street, showing the New York Telephone Company Building being enlarged. This structure, occupying an irregular shaped plot between Walker and Lispenard Streets, includes the old building and which is identifiable, same being the darker portion.

March 19, 1932

P. L. Sperr
